Problem 1

1.1 Graphing a bivariate function and its second order approximation

library(plot3D)

x <- seq(from= -pi/4, to = pi/4, length.out = 30)
y <- seq(from = pi/4, to = 3*pi/4, length.out = 30)
fun_f <- function(x,y){cos(x*y)}
fun_h <- function(x,y){1-((pi^(2))/8)*(x)^2}

z_fun_f<- outer(x, y, fun_f) # Outer Product for z value fun_f
z_fun_h <- outer(x, y, fun_h) # Outer Product for z value fun_h

persp3D(x = x, y = y , z = z_fun_f, col = "red", alpha = .5, xlab = "X1", ylab = "X2", 
main = "Taylor approximation of cos(X1*X2)")
persp3D(x = x, y = y , z = z_fun_h, col = "blue", alpha = .5, add = TRUE)

Absolute Value Error Function

abs_err <- abs(z_fun_f - z_fun_h)

persp3D(x = x, y = y, z = abs_err, xlab = "X1", ylab = "X2", 
main = "The  error in second order Taylor expansion of cos(X1*X2)", alpha = .5)

1.2 Plot the constant value contours for e(x1,x2), and explain the magnitude at several locations.

contour(x = x, y = y, z = abs_err, xlab = "X1", ylab = "X2", main = "The error in second
        order Taylor expansion of cos(X1*X2)")

At the x,y coordinations (0,0) both the f function and the h function are equal to 1, hence zero Error. This also the case when (0,x2) given that for these values (where x2 ranges), both the f and h function equal 1. Because the h function is a negative parabola it does not keep up with the periodic cosine function that decreases at a slower rate. For a fixed x1, ex: x1 = -.5 , the f function increases and decreases periodically from 1 to 2, maintaing a constant rate of error.

Problem 2

2.1 2nd Order Taylor Expansion of Bivariate Normal

bi_norm_exp <- function(x,y,m1,m2,d11,d12,d21,d22){1/(2*pi*((d11*d22)-(d12*d21))^(1/2))-
    (1/(8*pi*((d11*d22)-(d12*d21))^(3/2)))*((x^2)*(2*d22-d12-d21)+x*(m1*(d12+d21-2*d22)+
                                  m2*(d12+d21))+y*(m1*(d12+d21)+m2*(d12+d21-2*d11)) 
                                + (m1^2)*2*d22+(m2^2)*2*d11+(y^2)*(2*d11-d12-d21))}

Where, d11,d12,d21,d22 represent the standard deviations with respect to their subscripts values for mean 1 and 2, and standard deviations 11,12,21,22 for 2b(i)

2.2 Plot Bivariate Normal

x <- seq(from= -3, to = 3, length.out = 30) # X range
y <- seq(from = -3, to = 3, length.out = 30)# Y range
m1 <- 0
m2 <- 0
d11 <- 1 # std_11
d12 <- -.3 # std_12
d21 <- -.3 # std_21
d22 <- 1 # std_22

# calculation of coeefficients for 2nd order taylor expansion given above values for 2b(i)
coeff <- rep(x = 0, 8)
coeff_fun <- for(i in 1:length(coeff)){
  if(i == 1){
    coeff[1] <- 1/(2*pi*((d11*d22)-(d12*d21))^(1/2))}
  if(i==2){
    coeff[2] <- -(1/(8*pi*((d11*d22)-(d12*d21))^(3/2)))}
  if(i==3){
    coeff[3] <- (2*d22-d12-d21)}
  if(i==4){
    coeff[4] <- m1*(d12+d21-2*d22)+m2*(d12+d21)}
  if(i==5){
    coeff[5] <- m1*(d12+d21)+m2*(d12+d21-2*d11)}
  if(i==6){
    coeff[6] <- 2*d22}
  if(i==7){
    coeff[7] <- 2*d11}
  else{
    coeff[8] <- 2*d11-d12-d21}
}

# bivariate normal taylor expansion for 2b(i)
bi_exp_i <- function(x,y){
  coeff[1] +coeff[2]*((x^2)*coeff[3] +x*coeff[4]+y*coeff[5]+coeff[6]+coeff[7]+ 
                        (y^2)*coeff[8])
}

#creation of 3D plot for biveariate normal 2b(i)
z_fun_i <- outer(x,y,bi_exp_i)

persp3D(x = x, y = y, z = z_fun_i)

# calculation of coeefficients for 2nd order taylor expansion given above 
# values for 2b(ii)
coeff <- rep(x = 0, 8)
coeff_fun <- for(i in 1:length(coeff)){
  if(i == 1){
    coeff[1] <- 1/(2*pi*((d11*d22)-(d12*d21))^(1/2))}
  if(i==2){
    coeff[2] <- -(1/(8*pi*((d11*d22)-(d12*d21))^(3/2)))}
  if(i==3){
    coeff[3] <- (2*d22-d12-d21)}
  if(i==4){
    coeff[4] <- m1*(d12+d21-2*d22)+m2*(d12+d21)}
  if(i==5){
    coeff[5] <- m1*(d12+d21)+m2*(d12+d21-2*d11)}
  if(i==6){
    coeff[6] <- 2*d22}
  if(i==7){
    coeff[7] <- 2*d11}
  else{
    coeff[8] <- 2*d11-d12-d21}
}

# bivariate normal taylor expansion for 2b(ii)
bi_exp_ii <- function(x,y){
  coeff[1] +coeff[2]*((x^2)*coeff[3] +x*coeff[4]+y*coeff[5]+coeff[6]+coeff[7]+
                        (y^2)*coeff[8])
}
